<h2>When Character Count Matters</h2>

<h3>Social media</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Twitter/X:</strong> 280 characters per tweet (URLs count as 23 chars)</li>
  <li><strong>Instagram captions:</strong> 2,200 characters (preview truncates at ~125)</li>
  <li><strong>Instagram bio:</strong> 150 characters</li>
  <li><strong>LinkedIn posts:</strong> 3,000 characters (preview collapses at ~210)</li>
  <li><strong>Facebook posts:</strong> 63,206 characters</li>
</ul>

<h3>SMS (text messages)</h3>
<p>
  Standard SMS messages use 160 characters per message. If you go over 160, it splits into two messages and you're charged twice. If your message contains any non-standard characters (accents, emojis, curly quotes), the limit drops to 70 characters per message.
</p>

<h3>SEO meta tags</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Meta title:</strong> Under 60 characters to avoid Google truncating it with "..."</li>
  <li><strong>Meta description:</strong> 120–155 characters for the full snippet to show in search results</li>
</ul>

<h3>Database fields and form inputs</h3>
<p>
  Database columns are defined with a maximum character length (VARCHAR(255), TEXT, etc.). Input forms validate character counts for phone numbers, postcodes, passwords, and usernames.
</p>

<h2>Converting Between the Two</h2>

<p>
  A rough approximation: average English words are 5 characters long, plus one space, making the average word about 6 characters with spaces.
</p>

<ul>
  <li>100 words ≈ 600 characters (with spaces)</li>
  <li>280 characters ≈ 46 words (for social media context)</li>
  <li>160 characters (SMS) ≈ 27 words</li>
  <li>155 characters (meta description) ≈ 25–28 words</li>
</ul>

<p>
  These are approximations — actual ratios vary based on vocabulary. Technical writing with long words has fewer words per character; casual writing with short words has more.
</p>

